full_text:
Paige, I hold the same views as you do on God and religion.  I believe in God, but it&#39;s not so much a matter of faith, as it is of observation (of nature and life and myself and others) that has brought me to the conclusion of the existence of a higher power, for example the fact that despite everything, people still thrive best when loved,and when they love... and find it oppressive and insulting in the end, for an institution to ask you to remain in its clutches if you have outgrown it.  It&#39;s like a parent that is possessive and does not want their children to gain independence, for fear of losing them. It is selfish.  Why have to walk slowly in my walk with God by retaining my religion, when I am already speeding toward God, independently of religion?    

--- In EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com, Paige Chavez &lt;magnolia.massage@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; I agree 100% with you SF...we are just beginning to emerge from institutionalized religion and leaning toward independent thinking, as a planet. Years of the &quot;powers that be&quot; grasping for ultimate control disguised as organized religion has made human beings afraid of free thinking. The beautiful part about the paranormal movement and related theories on the afterlife is that we can now use scientific instruments to legitimize what we believe. I, for one, believe in God, or a supreme being and intelligent design.....just not the way I was instructed to believe. It&#39;s quite comforting to be able to discuss this way of life (and death) with people of the same convictions. Im thankful for all of you guys.....even the skeptics that keep us on our toes.
